          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">For many longtime c=
able heads, last week=E2=80=99s news of Warner Bros. Discovery=E2=80=99s di=
stribution deal with Charter was unequivocally the talk of the town. The <i=
>Journal</i>, after all, <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFp=
bF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dSX2JWVEpkM1JqNlhmbVVLRWtlWT0iLCJocmVmIjo=
iaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9idXNpbmVzcy9tZWRpYS93YXJuZXItYnJvcy1kaXNjb3Zlcn=
ktc2lnbnMtbmV3LWRpc3RyaWJ1dGlvbi1kZWFsLXdpdGgtY2hhcnRlci1lYmE0M2JmYz91dG1fY=
2FtcGFpZ249VGhlK1ZhcnNpdHkrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjg5JTJGMTYlMkYyNCUyOVx1MDAy=
NnV0bV9jb250ZW50PVRoZStWYXJzaXR5Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4OCUyRjI5JTJGMjQlMjl=
cdTAwMjZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW=
9cdTAwMjZ1dG1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3Z=
GE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjEwMzU5NDd9/470a32b72b7e308bf8ef5200adbf5d47836=
97514447a8eee864568f2bd29d589" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;=
font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">reported</a></u> the news with a press-rele=
ase-adjacent story featuring a subhead that heralded the =E2=80=9Cstable fe=
es=E2=80=9D for the mediaco despite the inevitable reality that it is going=
 to lose its NBA rights after next season. Talmudic interpreters of the top=
ic, however, sensed the invisible hand of <b>John
Malone</b>=E2=80=94the pioneering so-called <i>cable cowboy</i>, who sits o=
n WBD=E2=80=99s board and owns a 26 percent stake in Charter via his Libert=
y Media. Malone, it seemed, had manifested a prosperous truce.<br/><br/>Why=
 else would Charter open up its WBD deal <i>a full year early</i>=E2=80=94a=
 nonstandard tactic to begin with, and one made doubly unlikely given the c=
ompany=E2=80=99s recent <i>vulnerability</i>? As WBD prepares to renegotiat=
e the fees for its cable assets at various points across the next year, riv=
al distributors like Comcast and DirecTV are <i>licking their chops</i> ove=
r the potential savings they can incur by bargaining down the fees for an N=
BA-less TNT. So why on Earth would Charter agree to keep that channel=E2=80=
=99s carriage fees flat?<br/><br/>For what it=E2=80=99s worth, sources I tr=
ust at <i>both</i> companies dismissed rumors of Malone=E2=80=99s involveme=
nt, <i>insisting </i>that he has generally stayed out of these types of neg=
otiations during the past few years. But the mere
specter of Malone=E2=80=99s involvement nevertheless gained traction when W=
BD=E2=80=99s stock soared by more than 10 percent after the deal was announ=
ced. Theories about his light touch proliferated when it was suggested that=
 this Charter deal could somehow set the template for future TNT deals with=
 Comcast and DirecTV.<br/><br/>In short, that=E2=80=99s nonsense. Don=E2=80=
=99t expect the Charter deal to become a template for TNT. As I=E2=80=99ve =
written <i>ad nauseam</i>, Comcast agreed to pay $2.5 billion for NBA right=
s partly to <i>grinfuck</i> <b>David Zaslav </b>and Malone=E2=80=94<b>Brian=
 Roberts </b>and his deal team knew that they could recoup at least some of=
 their capital outlay from their forthcoming WBD negotiation. (WBD=E2=80=99=
s deal with Comcast for the former Warner Media assets, including TNT, is u=
p toward the end of next year.)<br/><br/>If Malone wasn=E2=80=99t pulling t=
he strings, though, why would Charter do this deal a year early? My sources=
 said that Charter wants to complete as many streaming deals
as possible <i>before</i> ESPN launches its direct-to-consumer =E2=80=9CFla=
gship=E2=80=9D product next year so that it can have a full complement of s=
ervices ready to go on that fateful day. So for Charter executives, the mos=
t consequential part of this deal had little to do with TNT=E2=80=99s rate.=
 Rather, the company was focused on getting the rights to make Max availabl=
e to its subscribers.<br/></td>
