          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Zaz referenced this=
 aspect of the deal during an appearance at a Goldman Sachs conference last=
 week, alluding specifically to Charter=E2=80=99s Spectrum product, which o=
ffers video, broadband, and an array of streaming services. =E2=80=9CIf you=
&#39;re a subscriber to Spectrum, you get the equivalent of $60 worth of st=
reaming services,=E2=80=9D Zaz said, describing Max=E2=80=99s position as a=
n =E2=80=9Canchor tenant=E2=80=9D in this new streaming bundle along with E=
SPN+, Disney+, Paramount+ and AMC+. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s also an uptake=
 incentive for Charter,=E2=80=9D Zaz said. =E2=80=9CWhy would you leave Cha=
rter to go somewhere else if you have this full bouquet? ... It will become=
 a significant economic revenue stream for Charter.=E2=80=9D Crucially for =
Zaz, WBD secured a wholesale rate for its Max streaming service=E2=80=94WBD=
=E2=80=99s fees are not dependent on subscribers signing up for the product=
=2E<br/><br/>Zaz, as my
partner <b>Bill Cohan </b>has previously noted, is leaning headfirst into a=
 new era of collaboration among legacy media players. While Netflix and Ama=
zon continue to pursue their manifest destiny to dominate the homescreens o=
f smart TVs and the buttons on connected remotes, the other guys are trying=
 to eke out money where they can, including via deals with their old cable =
distribution counterparts. It may not sound innovative, but it=E2=80=99s a =
telling and intelligent (and necessary) strategy amid streaming=E2=80=99s e=
ra of capital optimization.<br/><br/><b>Robert Fishman</b>, a financial ana=
lyst with MoffettNathanson, also noted that the guaranteed streaming cash w=
as more significant than any harbinger of TNT=E2=80=99s future value. =E2=
=80=9CIn other words, WBD got closer to the Disney+ deal of getting a whole=
sale rate for all Charter subscribers with access to a free Max subscriptio=
n, versus the Paramount+ deal with a wholesale rate for each subscriber tha=
t uses a free Max subscription,=E2=80=9D
Fishman wrote in a note. =E2=80=9CWe think this side of the deal can also b=
e counted as a win for WBD.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>These types of negotiations h=
ave changed radically, of course, as distributors cope with bloated bundles=
 and shrinking subscriber numbers. Both Charter and DirecTV, which solved i=
ts distribution problems with Disney on Saturday morning, touted the stream=
ing concessions they negotiated even more than the channel rates. For years=
, distributors would complain loudly about the broadcasters=E2=80=99 stream=
ing services. After all, WBD used money from its TNT license fees to sign a=
 USA Soccer deal that includes several exclusive matches on Max. ESPN+ and =
Hulu carry exclusive NHL games.<br/><br/>The Charter-WBD and DirecTV-Disney=
 deals, announced within days of each other, mark a strategy change for dis=
tributors. Now, instead of fighting the networks when they stream sports, t=
hey have decided to play ball with them. These days, of course, they=E2=80=
=99re kind of all on the same
team.<br/></td>
